<div id="stitle" style="display:none;">Notebook Entry</div>
<dl id="n26240d"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n26" href="#n26240d">N26 (VI.B.18)</a>:  <a href="../../ff/fnbs/n26all.htm#n26240d"> 240(d)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> navning</blockquote> <dd class="well"> <blockquote class="sources">But a peculiar, and in its results highly important, judicial institution prevailed in the North, namely &ldquo;<i>N&aelig;fn</i>,&rdquo; &ldquo;<i>N&aelig;fninger</i>&rdquo; (<mark>N&aelig;vninger</mark>); or, as it has been called in later times in English, &ldquo;Jury.&rdquo; According to the most ancient Danish laws the accuser had a right, particularly in important criminal causes, to select from among the people a certain number of jurors (N&aelig;vninger), who, after taking an oath, were to condemn or acquit the accused; and judgment was not pronounced till they had given their verdict. <font color="green">[<cite>An Account</cite> 165: It would, indeed, have been quite inexplicable that the Danes should have given up their peculiar Scandinavian <i>N&aelig;vn</i> in a country like England, where the Danish law obtained by degrees so extensive a footing that, during the reign of the first Norman kings, it was still in force in one-half of the kingdom.]</font> <small> Jens Jacob Asmussen Worsaae, <a name="JJAW1" href="../../ff/fdra/fdex.htm#JJAW1"><cite title="source">An Account of the Danes and Norwegians</cite></a> (1852) 161</small></blockquote> </dd></dl>
